{{ review_prompt_prefix }}Review the changes for issues. Use .fix-die-repeat/review.md as historical context.
Your task is ONLY to identify and document issues introduced by these changes. Do NOT fix them yourself.
Note: You do not have access to 'edit' or 'bash', so you cannot apply fixes even if you wanted to.

Classify issues as:
- [CRITICAL]: Security vulnerabilities, data loss/corruption, correctness bugs, broken builds, performance regressions, or violations of project policy.
- [NIT]: Style issues, minor optimizations, comments, formatting.

CRITICAL REVIEW CHECKLIST (LANGUAGE-AGNOSTIC):
- [ ] Security: no injection flaws, auth/permission bypasses, secret exposure, unsafe deserialization, or insecure defaults; files recreated after deletion/rotation re-enforce secure permissions (not relying on initial setup alone)
- [ ] Performance: no obvious regressions, unbounded growth, heavy work in hot paths, or N+1 style patterns; check for redundant function/API calls across overlapping call chains (e.g., a caller and callee both performing the same operation)
- [ ] Correctness/reliability:
    - No missing input validation (especially for external tool output or parsed JSON/YAML)
    - User inputs are normalized (e.g., case-insensitive, trimmed) and validated with strict parsing (e.g., specific type conversion instead of loose casting)
    - Validation runs consistently across all code paths (not skipped by early returns)
    - No unsafe error handling, resource leaks, or concurrency hazards
    - File I/O and locking best practices: lock scope/byte ranges/seek position plus atomic append/locking for shared artifacts
    - Blocking network/IO operations (including timers, retries, polling, backoff loops) are cancellation/abort-aware and have timeouts so execution or shutdown is not delayed
    - Test fixtures match implementation expectations
    - Early returns or edge case handling include appropriate user-facing notifications (no silent failures)
    - Boundary conditions analyzed for edge values (empty strings, zero as sentinel, null/root paths) with appropriate fallbacks
    - Equivalent user flows produce semantically consistent results (e.g., two paths that achieve the same outcome store the same data representation)
    - Algorithm implementations (truncation budgets, allocation splits) match their documented contracts
    - Operations ordered so failures happen before user-visible side effects (e.g., validate/subscribe before posting messages)
    - HTTP/stream response bodies consumed at most once (store in a variable before branching)
    - Retry/attempt counters incremented before the operation, not after success, so transient failures consume retries
    - Functions documented as "never throws" or "fail-silent" have error handling on all internal syscalls (filesystem, network)
    - Wrapper/utility methods don't perform unintended side effects beyond their stated purpose (e.g., a "check existence" method should not create resources; a "subscribe" method should not auto-create the target)
    - API responses scoped by permissions or visibility don't make absolute claims (e.g., prefer "not visible to this client" over "does not exist" when the API cannot distinguish the two)
    - Layered validation does not produce duplicate or conflicting error messages for the same field (e.g., an "invalid format" error should suppress a subsequent "missing required field" error for the same input)
- [ ] Data serialization: structured outputs (JSON/YAML/etc.) use safe serializers (not string interpolation) and are normalized/validated against expected schema when appending or combining documents before persisting
- [ ] Code quality:
    - No unjustified suppression of errors or warnings
    - Avoid terminating the process from library/orchestration code (return status instead)
    - Ensure CLI/entrypoint layers propagate internal failure codes to process exit status
    - Return helper results instead of discarding them or duplicating return logic
    - Use validated/narrowed local variables consistently (don't reach back to unvalidated input objects)
    - Prefer explicit guards/failures
    - Check for duplicated validation/parsing logic across multiple entry points and recommend shared helpers/constants
    - Use centralized constants/config defaults instead of hard-coded duplicate values
    - Related configuration values share consistent sourcing (when one is overridden, related values must be cleared or co-updated)
    - Empty or whitespace-only environment variable values are treated as "not set" rather than overriding valid configuration from other sources
    - Singleton/once-per-lifecycle initialization is verified (e.g., file truncation, cache seeding)
- [ ] Accuracy:
    - Docs/prompts/config instructions and examples match actual behavior and required fields (no false claims)
    - Type definitions in code match their documentation (e.g., docstrings, comments)
    - Cross-reference template instructions with corresponding validation schemas to ensure emitted fields are actually validated
    - User-facing logs/errors clearly explain limits, skips, or partial results (especially for fallback paths and edge cases)
    - Error/validation messages match the specific failure type (not generic catch-all text)
    - Non-obvious platform-specific behavior, concurrency patterns, or API quirks have inline documentation
    - Platform-specific commands check for availability or provide fallbacks
    - All declared/parsed configuration options are actually referenced and used in code (no dead config)
    - README/doc examples validated against actual formatter or output code (sample messages, CLI output, config snippets match real behavior)
    - Inline comments accurately reflect variable scope, lifecycle, and all code paths that reach them (especially after adding new conditions or filtering logic)
- [ ] Testing:
    - New utility classes, functions with platform-specific code paths, or complex logic have corresponding unit tests
    - Tests assert observable behavior (no empty tests that only exercise code paths)
    - Test logic actually exercises intended paths (no early-return skips/silent passes; not unreachable due to environment constraints)
    - Tests that mutate global state (e.g., environment variables, global mocks, system clock) properly restore it in teardown/cleanup blocks
    - Async tests wait for all asynchronous operations—no unawaited tasks or futures with assertions that could be skipped or silently pass
    - Mock/timer/global setup must have symmetric teardown (every mock/fake setup needs a guaranteed restoration in teardown or finally)
    - Shared module-level mutable state (queues, registries, caches) is reset in setup hooks to prevent order-dependent test results
    - Test environment variables are cleared/controlled in setup rather than inheriting host values
    - Allocated filesystem resources (temp directories, created files) have corresponding cleanup in teardown
    - Test assertions match actual API contracts—check for presence vs absence of optional fields and verify schema alignment between test expectations and implementation
    - Mocks/patches are actually exercised, mock return values match real outputs, and tests avoid redundant real I/O when mocks already cover the path
